==English==

===Etymology===
From {{m|en|subjunctive}} (from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|subjunctivus}}, from {{m|la|sub-||under}} + {{m|la|junctus||joined}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|jungere||to join}} + adjective suffix {{m|la|-ivus}}) + {{m|en|mood}} (from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|modus}}).

===Noun===
{{examples|
* ''If John '''were''' here, he would know what to do.''
* ''If this '''be''' liberty, then give me death!''
* ''I wish that I '''were''' there.''
* ''I want that he '''go'''.''
}}
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|grammar}} [[mood#Etymology_2|Mood]] expressing an action or state which is [[hypothetical]] or [[anticipated]] rather than [[actual]], including [[wish]]es and [[command]]s.
#: {{syn|en|conjunctive|conjunctive mode|conjunctive mood|subjunctive|subjunctive mode}}

====Usage notes====
Subjunctive mood is used much more in some other languages, such as Spanish and Latin, than it is in English. Apart from the third-person singular form without the suffix -('''e''')'''s''' (''I want that he '''go'''''), modern English has only one verb that has mutually distinguishable [[indicative mood|indicative]] and subjunctive forms &mdash; {{m|en|be}}.

:* {{m|en|be}} (subjunctive present, all persons except for archaic second-person singular)
:: {{ux|en|I suggest that that measure '''be''' taken.}}
:: {{ux|en|It is important that we all '''be''' at the meeting.}}
:* {{m|en|beest}} (archaic second-person singular, subjunctive present)
:: {{RQ:Shakespeare Tempest|act=III|scene=II|passage=Stephano!—If thou '''beest''' Stephano, touch me, and speak to me; for I am Trinculo:—be not afeared—thy good friend Trinculo.}}
:* {{m|en|wert}} (archaic second-person singular, subjunctive past)
:: {{R:King James Version|Job|8|6|passage=If thou '''wert''' pure and upright; surely now he would awake for thee, {{...}}}}
:: {{R:King James Version|Revelation|3|15|passage=I know thy works, that thou art neither cold nor hot: I would thou '''wert''' cold or hot.}}
:* {{m|en|were}} (subjunctive present, all persons except for archaic second-person singular)
:: {{ux|en|If John '''were''' here, he would know what to do.}}
:: {{ux|en|If they '''were''' in trouble, I would help them.}}

See also the conjugation at ''[[be#Conjugation|be]]''.

